{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018bon9DfyztxJo4rLJS1iXT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The tests are still timing out. The `toFake` option is being applied but `waitFor` still doesn't work. The problem is the `beforeEach` with `vi.useFakeTimers({ toFake: [\"setTimeout\", \"clearTimeout\"] })` — but `waitFor` may also use `Promise` or other things.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The issue could be that even with `toFake: [\"setTimeout\", \"clearTimeout\"]`, when Vitest tries to mock `setTimeout`, it affects ALL setTimeout including those inside `@testing-library/react`.\n\nActually wait — let me re-read the code. \n\nThe `waitFor` function from `@testing-library/react` uses `setInterval` to poll, not `setTimeout`, and `setInterval` isn't in my `toFake` list. But I'm realizing `waitFor` might also rely on microtasks or `MutationObserver` to detect DOM changes, which wouldn't be affected by fake timers at all. Looking at the actual error, the first `waitFor` call is timing out, which suggests the polling mechanism itself isn't advancing properly.\n\nWhen I set up fake timers with only `setTimeout` and `clearTimeout` faked, the `useEffect` runs and calls `fetchUsers`, which returns a resolved promise. That should work fine since `fetch` resolves as a microtask. But then `setLoading(true)` gets called synchronously, and I'm wondering if the issue is that `waitFor`'s polling can't advance without the timer it's actually using being faked. I need to reconsider the root cause here. The first batch of tests passes with real timers, but everything breaks once I introduce fake timers—even partial ones. The real problem is that `waitFor` likely depends on `setTimeout` for its timeout mechanism, so mocking it breaks the polling entirely. Instead of fighting with `waitFor`, I should manually advance time using `act()` and control the async flow directly within each test. I think the right approach is to let the initial fetch complete with real timers using `waitFor`, then switch to fake timers for the debounce test, advance the timer to trigger the debounce, and finally flush any pending async operations before asserting the results.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2129,"cache_read_input_tokens":62784,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2129,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a95ae396-124a-4cd9-a015-7f076b7b8d80","uuid":"b02bf01d-22e7-45cf-8a45-160abddf4737"}
